Jessie hails from Massachusetts, and this will be her first year teaching after several years‚Äô experience through substituting, paraprofessional positions, and coordinating an after-school program. What she loves most about working with kids is being a role model and inspire them to be excited and motivated about their learning. Her goal is to have her students leave the classroom feeling confident in all their abilities, not only academically but outside of the classroom as well!

Jessie enjoys spending time with friends and family and caring for her dog Cooper and cat Sadie. She loves reading (huge Stephen King fan), traveling, yoga, and tending to her growing house plant collection! Welcome to Fuller School, Jessie!

We are all in this together - let's be patient and support each other on behalf of all our students!

post_text:
All schools shall implement frequent hand washing procedures that align with the CDC Guidance Considerations for Schools. While hand sanitizer has become an acceptable and convenient way to clean hands, the best method for maintaining hand hygiene is with soap and water. Here are the five steps to washing your hands the right way as recommended in the "CDC When and How to Wash Your Hands" guidelines:

1. Wet your hands with clean, running water (warm or cold), turn off the tap, and apply soap.
2. Lather your hands by rubbing them together with the soap. Lather the backs of your hands, between your fingers, and under your nails.
3. Scrub your hands for at least 20 seconds. Need a timer? Hum the ‚ÄúHappy Birthday‚Äù song from beginning to end twice.
4. Rinse your hands well under clean, running water.
5. Dry your hands using a clean towel or air dry them.

Hand hygiene will begin as soon as anyone enters the buildings. A hand sanitizing station shall be located at the entrance and upon arrival, all students, staff and essential visitors shall sanitize their hands.

post_text:
¬°Hola! (Don't worry about trying to say my last name. You can call me Mr. B. -- or Profe B. in Spanish.)
The proud hiking companion of two dare-devil rabbits, I'm coming to KMS in my sixth year of teaching Middle School Spanish. I am actually coming back to the area: I used to work down the road in Hancock, teaching outdoor skills at a magical place called Sargent Camp, many moons ago. In recent years, however, I have taken on the rewarding work of teaching Spanish in the classroom. I am so glad to be back in the Monadnock Region!

The thing I love most about teaching Spanish is helping learners express themselves and their ideas in a new language, as they discover for themselves the best-kept secret of language-learning: It's easier than you think! After all, our brains are hard-wired for language!

When I'm not teaching, you can find me in one of three places: curled up with a good book, out among the trees and mountains of New Hampshire, or on a paddleboard crewed by Captain Hatchet (the gray one) and First Mate Auger (the white one).

We will shortly have an app available for daily morning screens as outlined in today's update. In a July 14th Press Release, CDC Director Dr. Robert Redfield is quoted as saying, ‚ÄúCloth face coverings are one of the most powerful weapons we have to slow and stop the spread of the virus ‚Äì particularly when used universally within a community setting. All Americans have a responsibility to protect themselves, their families and their communities.‚Äù

ALL students and staff members shall wear a face covering while at school, unless a medically documented accommodation is required. Each district will make a reusable, washable face covering available for every student and staff member upon request.

Anyone arriving at a school (students, staff, and essential visitors) without a covering will be provided a disposable face covering prior to entry into the building.

The screening solution we are implementing for our school buildings will include a series of prompts consistent with the current CDC Screening Guidelines as of July 31, 2020 (https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/schools-childcare/symptom-screening.html).

The prompts will ask people to respond to:
- Temperature of 100.4 or higher
- Sore throat
- New uncontrolled cough that causes difficulty breathing
- Shortness of breath
- Diarrhea, nausea, vomiting, or abdominal pain
- Fatigue, body aches, headache
- Loss of taste or smell

post_text:
The screening solution we are implementing for our school buildings will include a series of prompts consistent with the current CDC Screening Guidelines as of July 31, 2020 (https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/schools-childcare/symptom-screening.html).

The prompts will ask people to respond to:
- Close contact (within 6 feet of an infected person for at least 15 minutes) with a person confirmed for COVID-19.

- Close contact (within 6 feet of an infected person for at least 15 minutes) with a person experiencing symptoms of COVID-19 or under quarantine for possible exposure.

- Any travel to/from areas outside of New England (VT, ME, MA, CT, RI) within the last 14 days (starting from the last day of their travel outside New England), irrespective of the mode of transportation for travel.

post_text:
Artwork by Thomas Nowill.

Students in Ms. Nelken's art class at Keene Middle School have been recording their experiences during the Covid pandemic through cartoons. All the art was created by students in their homes while receiving online instruction, using their own art supplies. The art shows both the difficulty of staying at home, online schooling, and being separated from friends. The work highlights our students' ability to thrive during these times through exercise, cooking, art, finding humor in the small things, and spending lots of time with family pets.

post_text:
Artwork by Anastasia Evans

Students in Ms. Nelken's art class at Keene Middle School have been recording their experiences during the Covid pandemic through cartoons. All the art was created by students in their homes while receiving online instruction, using their own art supplies. The art shows both the difficulty of staying at home, online schooling, and being separated from friends. The work highlights our students' ability to thrive during these times through exercise, cooking, art, finding humor in the small things, and spending lots of time with family pets.

July 16 at 7:18 PM ¬∑

Today a very talented and dedicated group of NHDI teaching artists came together to offer a free outdoor pop-up class to a group of dancers whose season was cut short.

Stay tuned for the final video piece that is in production.

Thank you to our amazing staff: Kristen Leach Lisa Egan Cook Danielle Fitzpatrick Linda Estabrook Tracy Koch Croteau Jess Lawler Codman Tasha S. Warshaw Ashley Morse

Southwestern Community Services, Inc. began offering the Summer Food Service Program to our community‚Äôs youth today. All area students, including those from SAU29 districts, are welcome to utilize the lunch program free of charge.

SCS is encouraging folks to take advantage of the curbside pick-up at Keene Middle School. The program is available Monday - Friday from June 29 through August 21. The meals will be available from 11:30 am until 12:30 pm.

For more information please see the attachment to today‚Äôs update or contact Rhonda Hull, SCS Community Food Coordinator at 603-719-4240 or rhull@scshelp.org

post_text:
Artwork by Anastasia Evans.

Students in Ms. Nelken's art class at Keene Middle School have been recording their experiences during the Covid pandemic through cartoons. All the art was created by students in their homes while receiving online instruction, using their own art supplies. The art shows both the difficulty of staying at home, online schooling, and being separated from friends. The work highlights our students' ability to thrive during these times through exercise, cooking, art, finding humor in the small things, and spending lots of time with family pets.

post_text:
Even a worldwide pandemic can't prevent Mr. Prior's annual trout release tradition from happening!

This is a big deal for the 5th graders at Fuller School as they have watched the trout grow and develop since they welcomed them into the classroom as eggs back in late January. The students learned about the life cycle, made observations of their development, and documented their progress in their science journals. The students observed the release of the brook trout into their natural habitat through the virtual classroom, and Mr. Prior recommended celebratory snacking in style: Goldfish, Swedish Fish, etc... üêü

post_text:
After 14 years at Keene High School, having served the last six as principal, Jim Logan is stepping down at the end of this academic year.

Jim says that what he has enjoyed "hands down" most during his time here were his daily interactions with the students, walking the halls, seeing student shows and watching them playing on the athletic fields. He often dropped in on classes of all kinds to see how everyone was doing, and he will be sorely missed by many. Jim, we wish you all the best with your future endeavors, and please come visit often! (Photo by Keene Sentinel)

This video shows his very first zoom recital with his fellow music studio pals and he performed Haydn Sonata no. 50 in D Major and a nice Chopin Waltz. His teacher made everyone dress up, and there were even students attending on zoom from Poland!

post_text:
Artwork by Wade Plaskiewicz.

Students in Ms. Nelken's art class at Keene Middle School have been recording their experiences during the Covid pandemic through cartoons. All the art was created by students in their homes while receiving online instruction, using their own art supplies. The art shows both the difficulty of staying at home, online schooling, and being separated from friends. The work highlights our students' ability to thrive during these times through exercise, cooking, art, finding humor in the small things, and spending lots of time with family pets.

What a great idea: The Colonial Theater in Keene is putting our KHS graduates into the spotlight! Through June 4th their marquee is honoring 2020 graduates for all the work they've put into reaching this moment in their life. They are also offering personal selfie opportunities! On May 27-29 from 4-7 pm, May 30 from noon-3 pm, and June 3-4 from 4-7 pm, 2020 graduates are invited to come to The Colonial (in cap and gown we hope) and the Colonial will personalize the marquee with their name for pictures (first come first served). Free popcorn snack provided, too!

Also, between now and June 5, any graduate who takes a photo under the Class of 2020 Marquee and posts their picture on Facebook or Instagram, tagging @colonialkeene, liking their page, and using the hashtag #colonialgrads will be featured on the Colonial's pages and entered into a drawing for movie passes or free concessions. Five graduates will be chosen on June 5 and contacted through the platform upon which they posted.

Le Plus Excellent! Amelia Opsahl, Junior at KHS won first place in "Le Grand Concours" - the national French contest - nationally and in the New Hampshire Chapter - Level 5 (highest level) - Platinum award! 3,969 students competed at level 5, and 68,790 competed in all levels - we are so proud of Amelia!

Silver awards were earned by Isabelle Fleuette (level 2) and Elizabeth Stanish (level 2)
Bronze awards were earned by Tori (Astoria) Fox (level 2), Fiona Fitzpatrick (level 2), Lauren Fabis (level 1)
Honorable mention: Lorah Murphy, Miranda Boswell, Karthik Chalumuri, Chloe Roy, Ainsley Hubbard, Gillian Cote, Adelyne Hayward, Brooke Oster and Meghan Ylitalo. Well done everyone!

We are very proud to announce that our own Jennifer Antosiewicz has been selected as "Early Childhood Educator of the Year" for the Monadnock Region. Jennifer is a Careers in Education Instructor at the Cheshire Career Center at Keene High School. This award program is sponsored by the Cheshire Children's Museum and Impact Monadnock/The Monadnock United Way.

"Jennifer was selected in part because of her ability to meet the needs of individual children, to demonstrate theory versus reality, and her communication expertise with children, families and her colleagues,‚Äù explains Deb Ganley from the Cheshire Children's Museum. ‚ÄúWe had so many excellent candidates. It was not an easy decision. Jennifer also has the responsibility of teaching future early childhood educators, so her example as a role model is critical in what she does.‚Äù

Congratulations on this great honor, Jennifer, and thank you for all your hard work on behalf of our students!

post_text: Our Chesterfield Poetree has leafed out nicely as we end our final week of Apri, the National Poetry Month. The tree has given us a place to come together with poetry during this time of remote learning. Students and staff have sent in over 70 poems on a variety of topics and in many different poetic forms. Each one has been printed on a leaf and added to the tree in the library that has passed through all of the seasons since last fall. Now it is blooming with poetry for the spring! We will be sharing some of the poems here over the next few days - they are quite amazing!

Experts say that dealing with your own anxiety can be the most powerful way to make sure your kids feel secure. If you or your children are feeling worried, learning how to deal with that anxiety in a healthy way can help the whole family be more resilient, both now and when the pandemic is finally over. Our counselors recommend this article:
https://childmind.org/article/anxiety-and-coping-with-coronavirus/?fbclid=IwAR0YCrjHcx_RKw2AOpKljtUVy4ylfI598E__0oaz6Aij8RhOzLmwngYsWQE

We want to be informed, but obsessively checking the news can lead to anxiety. Some tips to consider:

- Stick to trustworthy sources
- Limit how often you check for updates.
- Step away from media if you start feeling overwhelmed.
- Ask someone reliable to share important updates.

Here is information you may find helpful: https://www.helpguide.org/articles/anxiety/coronavirus-anxiety.htm

April is Child Abuse Prevention Month. DHHS urges everyone to be on alert for signs of child abuse and neglect, as we all play a part in promoting the well-being of children and families throughout New Hampshire. To report child abuse or neglect, please call (800) 894-5533 (in-state) or (603) 271-6562.
More info on warning signs here: https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/dcyf/cps/signs.htm or https://preventchildabuse.org/resource/parenting-tip-signs-of-abuse-and-neglect/

April is Child Abuse Prevention Month. DHHS urges everyone to be on alert for signs of child abuse and neglect, as we all play a part in promoting the well-being of children and families throughout New Hampshire. To report child abuse or neglect, please call (800) 894-5533 (in-state) or (603) 271-6562.
More info on warning signs here: https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/dcyf/cps/signs.htm or https://preventchildabuse.org/resource/parenting-tip-signs-of-abuse-and-neglect/
